Homogeneous transformations in 22D



The matrix A𝐓B{^A}\bm{T}_B has a very specific structure and belongs to the special Euclidean group of dimension 22 or 𝐓∈𝐒𝐄(2)\bm{T} \in \bm{SE}(2).
This matrix is often referred to as a rigid-body motion.




Properties of homogeneous transformations


𝐓=[cθ−sθxsθcθy001]
\bm{T} = \begin{bmatrix}
c_\theta & -s_\theta & x \\ s_\theta & c_\theta & y \\ 0 & 0 & 1
\end{bmatrix}

A concrete representation of relative pose ξ\xi is ξ∼𝐓∈𝐒𝐄(2)\xi \sim \bm{T} \in \bm{SE}(2) and 𝐓1⊕𝐓2↦𝐓1𝐓2\bm{T}_1 \oplus \bm{T}_2 \mapsto \bm{T}_1\bm{T}_2 which is the standard matrix multiplication
𝐓1𝐓2=[𝐑1𝐭101×21][𝐑2𝐭201×21]=[𝐑1𝐑2𝐭1+𝐑1t201×21].
\bm{T}_1 \bm{T}_2 = 
\begin{bmatrix}
\bm{R}_1 & \bm{t}_1 \\ \bm{0}_{1 \times 2} & 1
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
\bm{R}_2 & \bm{t}_2 \\ \bm{0}_{1 \times 2} & 1
\end{bmatrix} = 
\begin{bmatrix}
\bm{R}_1\bm{R}_2 & \bm{t}_1 + \bm{R}_1t_2 \\ \bm{0}_{1 \times 2} & 1
\end{bmatrix}.

One of the algebraic rules was ξ⊕0=ξ\xi \oplus 0 = \xi. For matrices, we know that 𝐓𝐈=𝐓\bm{T} \bm{I} = \bm{T}, where 𝐈\bm{I} is the identity matrix. So for pose, we make the identification 0↔𝐈0 \leftrightarrow \bm{I}.
Another rule was that ξ⊖ξ=0\xi \ominus \xi = 0. We know for matrices that 𝐓𝐓−1=𝐈\bm{T} \bm{T}^{-1} = \bm{I}, which implies that ⊖𝐓↔𝐓−1\ominus \bm{T} \leftrightarrow \bm{T}^{-1}.
Finally, for a point 𝐩\bm{p} in homogeneous representation, we have 𝐓•𝐩↔𝐓𝐩\bm{T} \bullet \bm{p} \leftrightarrow \bm{Tp}, which is a standard matrix-vector product.








