Basic rotation matrices
The rotation matrices representing a rotation of θ\theta about the xx-, yy-, and zz-axes are



𝐑x,θ=[1000cθ−sθ0sθcθ]
\bm{R}_{x,\theta} = 
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & c_\theta & -s_\theta \\ 0 & s_\theta & c_\theta
\end{bmatrix}



𝐑y,θ=[cθ0sθ010−sθ0cθ]
\bm{R}_{y,\theta} = 
\begin{bmatrix}
c_\theta & 0 & s_\theta \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ -s_\theta & 0 & c_\theta
\end{bmatrix}



𝐑z,θ=[cθ−sθ0sθcθ0001]
\bm{R}_{z,\theta} = 
\begin{bmatrix}
c_\theta & -s_\theta & 0 \\ s_\theta & c_\theta & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1
\end{bmatrix}







Recall from Euler’s rotation theorem that any rotation can be represented by not more than three rotations about coordinate axes.
This means that an arbitrary rotation between frames can be decomposed into a sequence of three rotation angles and associated rotation axes.









Method 1



Imagine a sequence of basic rotations that place frame {0}\{0\} triad onto frame {1}\{1\}.

First apply a initial rotation of 𝐑x,−90∘\bm{R}_{x,-90^\circ},
Then apply a rotation of 𝐑z,−45∘\bm{R}_{z,-45^\circ} to the current axes.



0𝐑1=𝐑x,−90∘𝐑z,−45∘=(1000010−10)(12120−12120001)=(1212000112−120).
{^0}\bm{R}_1 = \bm{R}_{x,-90^\circ}\bm{R}_{z,-45^\circ} = \begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \\ 0 & -1 & 0
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} & \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} & 0 \\ -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} & \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix} = 
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} & \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \\ \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} & -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} & 0
\end{pmatrix}.










Method 2


Using the definition of a rotation matrix, compute the direction cosines.

0𝐑1=[𝐱1⋅𝐱0𝐲1⋅𝐱0𝐳1⋅𝐱0𝐱1⋅𝐲0𝐲1⋅𝐲0𝐳1⋅𝐲0𝐱1⋅𝐳0𝐲1⋅𝐳0𝐳1⋅𝐳0]=[cos45∘cos45∘cos90∘cos90∘cos90∘cos0∘cos45∘cos135∘cos90∘]=[1212000112−120]
\begin{aligned}
{^0}\bm{R}_1 =
\begin{bmatrix}
\bm{x}_1 \cdot \bm{x}_0 & \bm{y}_1 \cdot \bm{x}_0 & \bm{z}_1 \cdot \bm{x}_0 \\
\bm{x}_1 \cdot \bm{y}_0 & \bm{y}_1 \cdot \bm{y}_0 & \bm{z}_1 \cdot \bm{y}_0 \\
\bm{x}_1 \cdot \bm{z}_0 & \bm{y}_1 \cdot \bm{z}_0 & \bm{z}_1 \cdot \bm{z}_0
\end{bmatrix} &= 
\begin{bmatrix}
\cos{45^\circ} & \cos{45^\circ} & \cos{90^\circ} \\
\cos{90^\circ} & \cos{90^\circ} & \cos{0^\circ} \\
\cos{45^\circ} & \cos{135^\circ} & \cos{90^\circ}
\end{bmatrix} \\
&=
\begin{bmatrix}
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} & \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 1 \\
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} & -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} & 0
\end{bmatrix}
\end{aligned}

Roll-pitch-yaw angles
 



𝐑\bm{R} described as a product of successive rotations about the principal coordinate axes zz, y′y^\prime, and x′′x^{\prime\prime} taken in a specific order.

First a yaw about zz through an angle ψ\psi,
Then pitch about the current y′y^\prime by an angle θ\theta,
Finally roll about the current x′′x^{\prime\prime} by an angle ϕ\phi.

The resulting transformation matrix is given by








ϕ\phi: roll, θ\;\theta: pitch, ψ\;\psi: yaw



𝐑=𝐑z,ψ𝐑y,θ𝐑x,ϕ=(cψ−sψ0sψcψ0001)(cθ0sθ010−sθ0cθ)(1000cϕ−sϕ0sϕcϕ)=(cψcθ−sψcϕ+cψsθsϕsψsϕ+cψsθcϕsψcθcψcϕ+sψsθsϕ−cψsϕ+sψsθcϕ−sθcθsϕcθcϕ)
\begin{aligned}
\bm{R} &= \bm{R}_{z,\psi}\bm{R}_{y,\theta}\bm{R}_{x,\phi} = 
\begin{pmatrix}
c_\psi & -s_\psi & 0 \\ s_\psi & c_\psi & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
c_\theta & 0 & s_\theta \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ -s_\theta & 0 & c_\theta
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & c_\phi & -s_\phi \\ 0 & s_\phi & c_\phi
\end{pmatrix} = 
\begin{pmatrix}
c_\psi c_\theta & - s_\psi c_\phi + c_\psi s_\theta s_\phi & s_\psi s_\phi + c_\psi s_\theta c_\phi \\
s_\psi c_\theta & c_\psi c_\phi + s_\psi s_\theta s_\phi & -c_\psi s_\phi + s_\psi s_\theta c_\phi \\
-s_\theta & c_\theta s_\phi & c_\theta c_\phi
\end{pmatrix}
\end{aligned}

The three angles ψ\psi, θ\theta, and ϕ\phi can be obtained for a given rotation matrix using a method that is similar to that used to derive the Euler angles above.

Running example: θ=−60∘\theta = -60^\circ, ϕ=30∘\phi = 30^\circ, and ψ=90∘\psi = 90^\circ.

Axis-angle representation



Rotations: not always performed about the coordinate axes.

Let the axis 𝐤=(kxkykz)⊤\bm{k} = \begin{pmatrix} k_x & k_y & k_z \end{pmatrix}^\top, expressed in {0}\{0\}, be a unit vector.

Find a rotation matrix 𝐑k,θ\bm{R}_{k,\theta} representing a rotation of θ\theta about axis 𝐤\bm{k}

The rotational transformation 𝐑=𝐑z,α𝐑y,β\bm{R} = \bm{R}_{z,\alpha}\bm{R}_{y,\beta} brings the world zz-axis into alignment with the vector 𝐤\bm{k}.
A rotation about the axis 𝐤\bm{k} is computed using a similarity transformation as

𝐑k,θ=𝐑𝐑z,θ𝐑−1=𝐑z,α𝐑y,β𝐑z,θ𝐑y,−β𝐑z,−α=𝐑−k,−θ. \bm{R}_{k,\theta} = \bm{R}\bm{R}_{z,\theta}\bm{R}^{-1} =
\bm{R}_{z,\alpha}\bm{R}_{y,\beta}\bm{R}_{z,\theta}\bm{R}_{y,-\beta}\bm{R}_{z,-\alpha}
= \bm{R}_{-k,-\theta}.



