Quaternions



Quaternion – extension of the complex number


We write a quaternion as a scalar plus a vector: 𝐪=s+𝐯=s+v1i+v2j+v3k, \bm{q} = s + \bm{v} = s + v_1 i + v_2 j + v_3 k,  where s∈ℝs \in \mathbb{R} and 𝐯∈ℝ3\bm{v} \in \mathbb{R}^3 and the orthogonal complex numbers ii, jj, and kk are defined such that i2=j2=k2=ijk=−1 i^2 = j^2 = k^2 = ijk = -1  and we denote a quaternion as 𝐪=s⟨v1,v2,v3⟩. \bm{q} = s \langle v_1, v_2, v_3 \rangle. 




Quaternions support addition and subtraction, performed element-wise, multiplication by a scalar and multiplication 𝐪1∘𝐪2=s1s2−𝐯1⋅𝐯2⟨s1𝐯2+s2𝐯1+𝐯1×𝐯2⟩, \bm{q}_1 \circ \bm{q}_2 = s_1s_2 - \bm{v}_1 \cdot \bm{v}_2 \langle s_1
\bm{v}_2 + s_2 \bm{v}_1 + \bm{v}_1 \times \bm{v}_2 \rangle,  which is known as the quaternion or Hamilton product.
If we write the quaternion as a 44-vector (s,v1,v2,v3)(s, v_1, v_2, v_3) then multiplication can be expressed as a matrix vector product 𝐪∘𝐪′=(s−v1−v2−v3v1s−v3v2v2v3s−v1v3−v2v1s)(s′v1′v2′v3′)=(s𝐈+(0−𝐯⊤𝐯𝐯̂))(s′v1′v2′v3′)
\bm{q} \circ \bm{q}^\prime = \begin{pmatrix}
s & -v_1 & -v_2 & -v_3 \\ v_1 & s & -v_3 & v_2 \\ v_2 & v_3 & s & -v_1 \\
v_3 & -v_2 & v_1 & s
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
s^\prime \\ v_1^\prime \\ v_2^\prime \\ v_3^\prime
\end{pmatrix} = \left( s\bm{I} + \begin{pmatrix}
0 & -\bm{v}^\top \\ \bm{v} & \hat{\bm{v}}
\end{pmatrix}\right) \begin{pmatrix}
s^\prime \\ v_1^\prime \\ v_2^\prime \\ v_3^\prime
\end{pmatrix}

